<font color="#FF0000">REAL GOOKS!!!!!</font><br>
<tt>Sun Aug 17 11:35:54 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Gerald;<br><br>
You wrote,<br>
Cook, if you must believe that all the troops you fought were &quot;Commie Gooks&quot; in order to feel that you fought honorably, I pity you,<br><br>
Gerald, I can't call you professor for some reason, much like i can't call Spatz &quot;Doc,&quot; <br>
I don't know what was in the hearts of those I fought against. I don't know if they truly believed that communist propaganda, I only saw the color of the NVA uniform they wore. I don't know why this bothers you so much.<br><br>
Was it because as an intelligence officer you never saw them? Is there guilt residing in you because of that?<br>
You must remember the war we fought in I Corps was a lot different then those that served below us. A lot of VC I've been told lived south of Chu Lai, I don't know if that's true but North of there, I'll give you the NVA unit designation if you like. <br>
Better yet the captain not the same one that was at the reunion his replacement recently send all sorts of slides that were taken during the time he was our CO. Among them over 40 slides of dead NVA communist gooks, dressed in their Sunday best. Sappers and officers along with their brand new communist made weapons. At least twenty slides of different communist made weapons, other slides showing the documents. Do you read Vietnamese, I will be glad to send you a copy of the certificates of promotion., we took off their dead bodies. If you like I'll gladly send you copies of those slides so that you can see them then tell me if they were local jokers or the real thing.<br><br>
Like, I have said, I do not know if I ever killed a VC, I only saw 12 of them dressed as VC once. Shot at them and a short time later we were ambushed by that same group, but they split after firing a short burst, broke off engagement as soon as we hit the deck.  That was no fun.<br><br>
The gooks I fought stayed around for the count. They loved the challenge, and got up real close where we could not call in arty. Close enough for us to hear them talking. They often called out to us, they were informed enough to know our unit's designation. Often challenged us. Powerful and equipped with enough firepower to command respect from us.<br>
Made them mad a few times but it was not because I was a macho killing machine. I never thought myself a warrior. I only did what I could. <br>
After raking their trench lines with hundreds of rounds, I could not understand why they were so mad at me, that is how naďve I was. Why did hey want to put out my gun? I only shot at them to keep their heads down while we removed our dead and wounded from their killing zones. <br>
It took awhile before I realized what I had done. Why they were so mad at me and the gun I carried. Did not even know what I had done until others told me and some did so only recently.<br>
I remember often, often, having to lay on my back while the paddie dike I was hiding behind was peppered with relentless incoming fire. Couldn't understand why they were picking on me, I remember telling Aggie my A-gunner, <br>
 &quot;Why don't they shoot at the other guys.&quot; <br><br>
Sorry it bothers you that I say I killed communist soldiers and not local jokers, but that is what I did. Glad to send you copies of the photos and you can determine yourself after all you were an intelligence officer? You can tell me if they were VC or NV. Hint they wore NVA uniforms and had I love Hanoi Hanna tattooed on their foreheads and arms. That's another one. NVA often did have tattoos on their arms with their unit's designation, just like the Corps, probably got them tattooed near the university at Berkley. <br><br>
Sorry gook also bothers you, As I have written before, there are words that I use here and in the book, that some may find offensive.  In today's society, they are not politically correct. I use them here because they are the words of war, words of that time and era. They are words we used in a Marine rifle squad that was made up of individuals from all across America. Blacks, Mexicans, and Whites, in the Marine Corps we enjoyed a common bond, a unity and relationship bonded by the Marine Corps green, we all wore. We used these words to describe the enemy, ourselves and a culture we did not understand. But that is the way it was then and it was our way of life.<br><br>
Only one side of the Vietnam experience has dominated the news media, much has never been historically visited. In order to move toward the future we may still have to re-explore the past. Disarm those bobby-traps and examine their marking, as to who manufactured them, who supplied the funds and equipment that supported their destructive power at home and abroad. Dialog begins with the past; accountability can not be one sided. You cannot go forward when shame still overshadows many of our American heroes. When they have never been properly honored because left wing agenda socialist want to move on, &quot;its in the past forget it they say,&quot; <br>
But the Vietnam Veteran needs those answers, going after the U.S. government is not going to give you those answers. You can lobby congress for vet benefits but that's not going to heal Vietnam Veterans  soul. Probably that's why I have never joined any service organization.<br>
When others and I speak about our Vietnam experiences and those we fought against their mouth falls open, and they change the topic, they want to talk about what our government did wrong. How wrong the war was. Speak to a Vietnamese in America today, and see how silent he is when you talk about fighting against (VC) but ask them to talk about us fighting against communist soldiers from the north and you will see their faces light up and they will talk, and talk. Greatest gift you can give a vet, is to hear from the lips of the Vietnamese in American how they felt about us being there. <br>

<p><code>-- There because we wanted the Real Thing!  (Cook Barela) </code><p>


